	(text "now, we need to power the esp32 module. \nfor this design, we'll generate 3.3V using\na linear regulator that can handle at \nleast 600 milliamps of output current.\n\na switching regular > LDO because switching\nregulators waste less heat (esp when stepping \ndown from 5V to 3.3V)\n\nbut we care more about simplicity than\nefficiency in this simple schematic"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 156.464 71.374 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
				(thickness 0.254)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "07df28ec-969c-4339-b114-50f83d19c06f")
	)
	(text "these are duplicates\nas USB-C is reversible.\nit can be plugged into\nany orientation so \ninternally the connector\nduplicates the USB 2.0 data\nlines"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 53.086 96.774 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.381 0.381)
			)
		)
		(uuid "0a1b7f51-3976-4ebb-b54f-d158590c0eb3")
	)
	(text "use pull-down resistors on these\npins to indicate our board is a power sink\n(it receives power, not gives it)"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 48.514 86.614 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.381 0.381)
			)
		)
		(uuid "11288c7a-dfe7-4658-b92a-e8e193dbabd5")
	)
	(text "it's essentially a\nreset button. if\nthe board crashes,\nwe can press the\nreset button instead\nof power recycling the\nentire board"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 146.304 149.098 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "13d7ecb7-5ca7-4563-8425-d48c6488719f")
	)
	(text "when this push is pulled low, chip resets.\nwhen it's held high, chip operates normally"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 157.48 143.764 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "18450dff-ab77-4976-831b-ad03def4f1c2")
	)
	(text "SHIELD connects to\nmetal shell of the\nUSB connector. SHIELD\nis typically tied to ground\neither directly or thru\nresistor/capacitor network\nto reduce noise"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 31.75 115.316 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "1b59c3e2-5dd7-4d7f-8c09-c09a82d33eac")
	)
	(text "FULL RUNDOWN OF SCHEMATIC:\n- Complete mini evaluation board design around the ESP32-C3-WROOM-02.\n- Started from the USB-C power input. \n- - Added protection and filtering. \n- Stepped down to 3.3V with an LDO.\n- Powered the ESP32 module correctly with proper decoupling. \n- - Added low-speed RTC crystal. \n- Implemented reset and boot circuitry. \n- Connected the USB data lines properly. \n- Exposed the IOs on pin headers for easy access."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 153.924 38.354 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "240cdfbc-50c7-4541-8bf6-fbe75e297e38")
	)
	(text "now we need to connect the USB-C to the ESP32.\nif we go to the datasheet and look at the \"Boot\nConfigurations,\" we'll see that teh native USB \ninterface is mapped to IO18 and IO19. these pins\nare internally connected to the USB peripheral\ninside the chip. \nthus, we need to connect D+ from the USB connector\nthrough the ESD protection device to the correct \nUSB data pin on the ESP32.\nthe same for D- too. \nit's really important D+ connects to correct + pin\nand D- connects to correct - pin"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 70.358 208.28 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "2631d38d-896f-4d35-8ea6-7fbcd78ec296")
	)
	(text "footprint defines the physical pad layout \nthat will appear on the PCB. footprint \nmust match the actual connector used\nso the appropriate USB-C receptable footprint\nthat matches the mechanical drawing in the \ndata sheet must be used"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 27.686 94.488 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "2cff7ede-27eb-4726-bd78-d4c7e41bbd5a")
	)
	(text "now we need to expose the GPIOs so \nthis board can actually function as\nan evaluation board. we want to \nbring the IO pins out to pin headers\nthat will sit along the edge of the PCB.\nthis makes it easy to plug the board\ninto a breadboard, connect jumper wires, \nor interface w/ external peripherals."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 119.888 186.69 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "2ec08fa1-d434-4afe-9d28-09d035761506")
	)
	(text ""
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 193.04 180.34 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "386cf364-da97-426e-aa3c-816f55cd1aee")
	)
	(text "this is the classic through-hole\nheader spacing that works well\nwith breadboards and jumper \nwires. after placing the two \n8-pin headers, we begin connecting\nthe IO pins (along w/ 3.3V and GND)\nto the header pins in a clean and \nlogical order."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 266.7 137.414 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "39e04669-e7cb-4d2a-acad-1f2931c754e8")
	)
	(text "with the pull-up resistor, \npush button, and RC filter\nin place, we have a reliable\nmanual reset circuit for the\nESP32"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 203.2 151.638 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "3be867cd-cde0-497f-809d-b330801da469")
	)
	(text "CC1 & CC2 are configuration channel pins\nused for cable orientation detection & to\nnegotiate power roles between devices\nUSB-C is reversible so only one of the CC pins\nwill be active depending on how the cable is\ninserted"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 26.162 103.886 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "47a71d60-7488-48fd-ac7e-f212ffbffe26")
	)
	(text "the usb-c is the main power \nsupply so we add that first"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 50.292 67.31 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
		)
		(uuid "48b95fd7-5431-4ebd-b25d-db133a751175")
	)
	(text "the AP2112 is a well-known 3.3V \nLDO that can handle the required\ncurrent and is easy to implement"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 177.038 68.58 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
				(thickness 0.254)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "641b3011-c823-465f-8286-ae55928f0080")
	)
	(text "D-s and D+s are the USB 2.0 data lines.\nthey're used for communication between\nhost and device\nimplementing usb data functionality means\nthese lines will connect to the microcontroller\nor to a USB to UART converter"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 56.134 103.886 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.381 0.381)
			)
		)
		(uuid "6475f191-66de-4100-a602-93e26406c364")
	)
	(text "3.3V LDO"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 191.008 104.902 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(face "Arial CE MT Black")
				(size 2.54 2.54)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "6ac8ce93-9009-40d7-ac9b-49b4af6edb09")
	)
	(text "EPS32"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 124.968 223.52 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(face "Arial CE MT Black")
				(size 2.54 2.54)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "6b90ddfb-5374-4490-a861-4b9b6a126131")
	)
	(text "take a look at the ESP-C3-WROOM-02 datasheet\nand go down to \"9 Peripheral Schematics.\" \nit recommends decoupling capacitors on the VDD\npin: 110 microfarad capacitor for bulk decoupling\nand 110 nanofarad capacitor for high frequency\ndecoupling"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 66.802 136.144 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
				(thickness 0.254)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "6c3de2ef-6fd2-44f7-9de5-33cf722c2e50")
	)
	(text "A zero-ohm resistor is \nthe series element."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 112.014 72.39 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "705291fe-b651-4c85-be4f-4375c3c281d2")
	)
	(text "VBUS = main power pin\nstandard USB provides 5V\nstandard power circuitry starts from this pin"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 46.736 80.01 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.381 0.381)
			)
		)
		(uuid "776f71fd-3fe5-49fc-9c59-2e6dc48d25bb")
	)
	(text "Input Power & USB-C"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 119.634 129.54 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(face "Arial CE MT Black")
				(size 2.54 2.54)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "784dcb28-3f95-4947-bb73-7e94137ee8fb")
	)
	(text "proper real-time clock functionality and \nlow power time keeping means we still need\nto include a low-speed crystal dedicated \nto the RTC domain. the esp32 datasheet \nrecommends a 32.768 kHz crystal for this \npurpose"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 42.164 220.726 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "7a0e9dcc-9b7d-46c9-a0fd-ff68daeaa8fd")
	)
	(text "when it comes to booting the ESP32,\nthere are 2 main boot modes. \nthe first one is SPI boot mode \n(default mode), where the chip boots\nfrom its internal flash memory.\nthe second one is download boot mode,\nwhich is used when we want to flash\nnew firmware onto the device.\n\nif you go to the datasheet and to \n\"4.1 Chip Boot Mode Control,\" we can\nsee that IO2, IO8, and IO9 are\nstrapping pins (special pins that\nare sampled during reset).\ntheir logic level at startup determines\nhow the chip will boot according to the\nboot configuration table in the data sheet."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 148.844 180.086 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.508 0.508)
			)
		)
		(uuid "7d02ddb5-20ed-4e5f-a8ce-dd283641063f")
	)
	(text "for IO2 and IO8, when\nthey're high in both \nnormal and download \nmodes, we simply add\n10k kilo ohm pull-up\nresistors to 3.3V.\nno need for buttons on\nthose pins"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 43.18 158.496 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "7e9dd9b9-24a5-47b4-bbf9-645ee6ed69cb")
	)
	(text "This is a simple filtering stage. It's a bidirectional RC \nfilter impelmented as a basic PI filter. It consists of 2\ncapacitors to ground and a series resistor between."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 121.666 67.818 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "84a79fc8-3fe5-4186-af15-6f3383a560ff")
	)
	(text "SBU1 and SBU2 are sideband use pins.\nin simple usb 2.0 designs, they're \nusually not used and left unconnected.\nthey're more relevant in advanced usb-c \napplications"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 60.452 113.538 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.381 0.381)
			)
		)
		(uuid "8774e315-ea3b-4bf7-90fd-a68c600af733")
	)
	(text "100 ohm resistor & 100 nanofarad\ncapacitor to ground is enough to\nmake a small RC filter. it smooths \nout the signal and prevents false\ntriggering due to contact bounce"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 194.31 143.256 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "8d9e4710-a35a-420b-9ea6-316cc5c6c29e")
	)
	(text "again, we want to keep the BOM as simple as possible.\nwe'll reuse the 4.7 microfarad capacitor that we're\ncurrently using, but for nanofarads, we'll put in the\n100 nanfarad capacitors since they're very important for\nhigh frequency filtering. they respond much faster to\nrapid current spikes and help keep the local supply stable\nat higher frequencies"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 107.188 137.668 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
				(thickness 0.254)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "9c2c65ec-53d2-4873-a8f4-08da18785737")
	)
	(text "Pin Headers"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 302.26 135.89 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(face "Arial CE MT Black")
				(size 2.54 2.54)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "a4c2aae1-f3fc-4a66-9a46-6430fd140a64")
	)
	(text "for download boot mode, IO9 needs\nto be pulled while IO2 and IO8 \nremain high. this means IO9 needs\nspecial handling. it must be pulled\nhigh by default, so the chip boots\nnormally. \nhowever, we also need a way to pull\nit low when we need to enter download\nmode. thus, we enter a similar\nconfiguration to what we did on the\nreset pin"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 197.358 182.88 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "b59ae177-dbe8-4710-9927-70feaa8aff4a")
	)
	(text "BOOT & Reset Buttons"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 205.74 135.89 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(face "Arial CE MT Black")
				(size 2.54 2.54)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "c1699ec8-6a42-44fd-b409-a4f6a1769fff")
	)
	(text "to implement this \nproperly, we need\na pull-up resistor\nand simple debounce\nnetwork"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 168.148 148.844 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.635 0.635)
			)
		)
		(uuid "cb0fd42a-e7ea-48ef-a2e0-5edfd6f444d9")
	)
	(text "click the AP2112 and you'll see a link\nthat leads to its datasheet. scroll down\nto page 2 and you'll see that the recommended\ninput capacitor value is 1uF (1u) but right now,\nwe only have 4.7u. instead of adding a new\ncapacitor value to the BOM, we'll use the current\n4.7u value. using 4.7 instead of 1 microfarads will\nnot cause any issues"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 178.816 75.184 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.508 0.508)
				(thickness 0.254)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "f0cf6979-4ac0-4f64-9b8a-d2e168daeac7")
	)
	(text "for the rest of these GPIO pins, for now, \nplace global ports on them. this keeps\nthe schematic clean and prepares the signals\nfor routing/expansion later. it also makes it\neasier to connect the pins to headers or circuitry\nwithout cluttering the page"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 98.552 173.228 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.508 0.508)
				(thickness 0.254)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "ff79cea4-5e80-4eda-861a-270310fc12c8")
	)
